              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Interventional Radiology (IR) offers minimally invasive alternatives to traditional surgery. At SALi, our skilled interventional radiologists use advanced imaging techniques like ultrasound, CT, and fluoroscopy to perform a variety of procedures for liver diseases.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                These procedures include transarterial chemoembolization (TACE) for liver cancer, TIPS for portal hypertension, and percutaneous biopsies. IR treatments often involve smaller incisions, less pain, and faster recovery times compared to open surgery.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Trans-Arterial Chemoembolization (TACE)</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                TACE is a highly effective treatment for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) and other liver tumors. The procedure involves delivering chemotherapy drugs directly to the tumor through its blood supply, followed by blocking (embolizing) the artery feeding the tumor. This dual mechanism starves the tumor while exposing it to high concentrations of chemotherapy.
              </p>
              <ul class="list-items list-unstyled mb-40 pl-40">
                <li><strong>Conventional TACE:</strong> Uses lipiodol mixed with chemotherapy drugs.</li>
                <li><strong>Drug-Eluting Beads TACE (DEB-TACE):</strong> Uses microspheres that slowly release chemotherapy over time.</li>
                <li><strong>Selective TACE:</strong> Targets specific tumor-feeding vessels for maximum effect and minimal liver damage.</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                TACE is typically performed as a day procedure or overnight stay. Multiple sessions may be needed for optimal tumor control. Side effects include post-embolization syndrome (fever, pain, nausea) which usually resolve within a week.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Radiofrequency Ablation (RFA)</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                RFA uses heat energy to destroy small liver tumors. A needle electrode is inserted into the tumor under imaging guidance, and radiofrequency energy creates heat that kills cancer cells. RFA is ideal for tumors less than 3-5cm in size and is often combined with other treatments.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Benefits:</strong> Minimal invasiveness, can be repeated if needed, preserves healthy liver tissue, suitable for patients who cannot undergo surgery, outpatient or short hospital stay.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Transjugular Intrahepatic Portosystemic Shunt (TIPS)</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                TIPS is a life-saving procedure for complications of portal hypertension due to cirrhosis. A stent is placed between the portal vein and hepatic vein to reduce pressure in the portal system, effectively treating:
              </p>
              <ul class="list-items list-unstyled mb-40 pl-40">
                <li>Recurrent variceal bleeding uncontrolled by endoscopic treatment</li>
                <li>Refractory ascites not responding to diuretics</li>
                <li>Hepatic hydrothorax (fluid in the chest)</li>
                <li>Budd-Chiari syndrome</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                TIPS is performed under conscious sedation through a neck vein approach. Patients are monitored for hepatic encephalopathy, which can be managed with medications.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Other Interventional Procedures</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Percutaneous Liver Biopsy:</strong> Image-guided needle biopsy to diagnose liver diseases, stage fibrosis, or confirm cancer diagnosis.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Biliary Drainage (PTBD):</strong> Placement of drains to relieve blocked bile ducts in patients with biliary obstruction.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Portal Vein Embolization:</strong> Pre-operative procedure to increase the size of the remaining liver before major liver resection.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Microwave Ablation:</strong> Alternative to RFA using microwave energy to destroy tumors.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Patient Safety and Care</h5>
